ce:section.ce:para:
Further studies were conducted to determine the selectivity of S2- to bind to Hg2+ in Hg2+-LUQDs solution without interference from other ions. Several solutions of anions (CH3COO–, SO4
                        2-and Cl-) and cations (Cu2+, Fe3+, Co2+, Zn2+, Mg2+, Na+, Pb2+, K+, and Cd2+) at 50 μM, were added to Hg2+-LUQDs solution. The FL intensity was tested at 360 nm in the absence and presence of S2-. From Fig. 4B, it was concluded that the FL intensity was enhanced mainly in the case of S2-, whereas other anions and metal ions were largely unaffected. Therefore, it is concluded that LUQDs are highly selective for the detection of S2- ions based on their ability to recover the FL intensity of the prepared dots. The emission intensity of the dots in Hg2+-LUQDs solution at 360 nm was quantitatively restored after S2- addition at concentrations of 10.0–150.0 μM (Fig. 4C,4D), with a correlation coefficient of 0.9999 and the LOD was estimated to be 1.35 μM, as illustrated in Supplementary Table S2 and the method accuracy was very good as shown in the Supplementary Table S3. The developed system provides a simple, time-saving, sensitive sensor for S2- ion detection (Table 2
                        ) among existing approaches.The LOD of the developed method is lower than or comparable to other S2- ion sensing methods (2.37 μM) [52] and (1.1 μM)[42]. The reported N-CDs method [53] has higher sensitivity for S2- ion than other reported methods and the developed one but suffers from long reaction time at higher temperatures and multi-step probe fabrication, which limits its use. The proposed method, although less sensitive than some reported approaches [53–58], is superior in that it is easy to prepare from green and available materials using microwave irradiation and doesn't require any post-synthesis modifications, which makes it easy to apply and implement.

Drinking water contaminated with S2- can be fatal at a very low dose. Since humans can be exposed to a concentration as low as 0.2 ppm of S2- 
                           [22,64], it is important to make water drinkable. At the same time, the regulatory limit of mercury concentration, according to the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), is 0.5 ppm in drinking water and Tuna fish samples [65]. To check the feasibility of developed dots as fluorescent probes, it was necessary to use LUQDs for quantification of both Hg2+ and S2- in river water, tap water, and sewage water samples. The LOD of our method for detecting Hg2+ and S2- are 0.012 and 0.045 ppb, respectively, which render the proposed method suitable for their analysis in environmental waters and food samples. The quenching in the FL emission intensities and their regaining of the fabricated dotswas recorded, and hence, the corresponding concentrations of Hg2+ and S2- ions in the initial unknown solutions could be easily determined. The experimental data were summarized in (Table 3
                           ), assuring excellent applicability and selectivity of LUQDs for estimation of S2- in environmental river waters, tap waters, and sewage waters with high recovery percent of 100.09 %, 100.01 %, and 99.93 %, respectively. For the Hg2+ assay, the recovery ranges between 99.45 % and 100.63 % in river waters, 99 % and 100.95 % in tap waters, 99.55 % and 100.5 % in sewage waters, and low RSD %.
